    preview: `The classic tale is used by Jain masters to teach Anekantavada—the doctrine of multiple viewpoints and intellectual humility.`,
    body: [
      `The story of the blind men and the elephant is a cornerstone of Jain philosophy, used to explain *Anekantavada* (the doctrine of non-one-sidedness).`,
      `Six blind men were asked to describe an elephant. The one touching the trunk said it was a snake; the ear, a fan; the leg, a tree; the belly, a wall; the tail, a rope; the tusk, a spear. They began to fight, each calling the others liars.`,
      `A wise Jain monk passed by and stopped the fight. 'None of you is lying,' he explained. 'You are all telling the truth, but only a *partial* truth (Naya). The elephant has all these features. You are fighting because you mistake your partial view for the *absolute* whole.'`,
      `Jainism uses this story to teach that reality is infinitely complex (Ananta-dharmatmak). Every viewpoint, every religion, and every philosophy holds a piece of the truth, depending on its perspective.`,
      `To say 'Only I am right, and everyone else is wrong' is an act of intellectual violence (Himsa). True Ahimsa is not just abstaining from physical harm; it requires *intellectual Ahimsa*—the humility to accept that others also hold valid pieces of the truth. When we apply *Syadvada* (the language of 'from one perspective...'), anger dissolves, dogmatism dies, and deep peace and tolerance emerge in society.`,
    ],
    phal: `Recognizing that truth is multi-faceted (Anekantavada) dissolves dogmatism. True non-violence requires intellectual humility and tolerance of diverse viewpoints.`,
